d steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":79,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":88,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Anne Spencer was born in 1470, in Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England. She married John Carlton Knight in 1466, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1560, in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1470–1560":"1470–1560","1467–1541":"1467–1541","1482–1564":"1482–1564","1558":"1558","1467":"1467","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1470":"1470","about 1482":"umbes 1482","1549":"1549","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England":"Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1470–1560":"1470–1560","1467–1541":"1467–1541","1482–1564":"1482–1564","1558":"1558","1467":"1467","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1470":"1470","about 1482":"noin 1482","1549":"1549","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England":"Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1470–1560":"1470–1560","1467–1541":"1467–1541","1482–1564":"1482–1564","1558":"1558","1467":"1467","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1470":"1470","about 1482":"environ 1482","1549":"1549","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England":"Charwelton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lady Anne Spencer est née en 1470, à Charwelton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé John Carlton Knight en 1466, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée en 1560, à Northampton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 90 ans."},"de":{"1470–1560":"1470–1560","1467–1541":"1467–1541","1482–1564":"1482–1564","1558":"1558","1467":"1467","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1470":"1470","about 1482":"um 1482","1549":"1549","Northampton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England","Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England":"Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England","lifeSummary":"Lady Anne Spencer wurde 1470 in Charwelton, Northamptonshire, England geboren. Sie hat 1466 in England, United Kingdom John Carlton Knight geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb 1560 im Alter von 90 Jahren in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England."},"ht":{"1470–1560":"1470–1560","1467–1541":"1467–1541","1482–1564":"1482–1564","1558":"1558","1467":"1467","1564":"1564","1541":"1541","1560":"1560","1482":"1482","1470":"1470","about 1482":"about 1482"